title: For Sale/Trade:  RARE Matching* Kokura Arsenal Arisaka Type 44 Cavalry Carbine for other Milsurp Rifles!
postcontent:
Hello! 
I'm looking to sell or trade my Kokura-Marked Type 44 Cavalry Carbine. The rifle is in it's factory state, without modifications. The Wood furniture is in fair condition, and the metal has lost some bluing but is otherwise intact. The bore is darkened, but the rifling is very sharp. Bolt locks and cycles smoothly, the bayonet folds in and out solidly, and there seems to be no major external or internal damage. The majority of the rifle is matching, as the front assembly, receiver, barrel, tang, trigger, and stock all match. The rear sight does not match the rifle, but all parts match. Other parts, like the magazine plate, bayonet release button, and bolt assembly are non-matching.Interestingly enough, this is the first production model of the Type 44, made in the early 30s, and the bolt is marked as the 22nd manufactured at the Kokura company. More photos can be seen here:http://imgur.com/a/Gp3rCFeel free to give me an offer.
I am willing to ship.If curious, I also have general information about the history of this specific rifle. It has a 1st production run bayonet lug, and with the exception of the bolt and small parts, all matches as number 962. It was manufactured in the Kokura Rifle manufacturing plant, likely in 1933. This rifle is not only very rare, but it is made even more rare by it's extremely low production number, the bolt is actually numbered as #22, the 22nd bolt manufactured for the Type 44. From here, there is no documented history for the rifle, but it is extremely likely that it was then used by Japanese Cavalry in the late invasion of Manchuria and saw extensive service as a cavalry rifle in the Japanese Manchuko Imperial Army, which can be speculated based on the grooving on the right side of the stock which shows that it thoroughly used by cavalry during this period. After the outbreak of WWII in 1940, it is likely that this rifle was re-arsenaled and expected to be repaired, but simply was not based on the lack of resources and left in an arsenal until the end of the war. From here, it was likely captured and brought back to the states, where the chrysanthemum marking was partially defaced (something a Japanese soldier would not do) based on an order from General McArthur. It must have been brought back following WWII, because it also lacks an import stamp. While all of this is purely research-based speculation, I am fairly confident that this is the rich history of the rifle.
